# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asian-cricket-council
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-elite-league] The first tournament of second division of ACC Premier League was held in Singapore between 7–13 June 2014.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-elite-league] Singapore won the tournament and qualified for 2016 ACC Premier League.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-elite-league] Saudi Arabia finishing second qualified for 2015 ICC World Cricket League Division Six.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-premier-league] The top four teams of top-tier tournament, Afghanistan, UAE, Nepal and Oman qualified for the 2014 ACC Championship, while Hong Kong and Malaysia remained in the 2016 ACC Premier League.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-premier-league] In the second division held in Singapore between 7–13 July, the host winning the tournament also qualified for the same tournament.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-premier-league] Results of the ACC Premier League 2014 was determined on rankings in the final table.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-premier-league] If two or more teams had equal points, rankings were decided by net run-rate.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-premier-league] The top five run scorers (total runs) are included in this table.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2014-acc-premier-league] The top five wicket takers (total wickets) are listed in this table.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The **2022 Asia Cup Qualification** was a men's cricket tournament which took place in Oman in August 2022 to determine qualification for the 2022 Asia Cup (which was originally scheduled to be played in 2020).
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The 2020 editions of the ACC Western and Eastern regional T20 tournaments were held in February and March of the same year by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Thirteen teams competed (eight in the Western and five in the Eastern event), with the aim of progressing to the qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] These were scheduled to be followed by the Asia Cup Qualifier tournament in Malaysia, which was due to be played in August 2020.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] However, in July 2020 the Asia Cup was postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, resulting in the postponement of the qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] In May 2021, the Asian Cricket Council confirmed that there would be no Asia Cup in 2021, with that edition of the tournament deferred until 2023.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] It was later announced that there would be a T20I Asia Cup in 2022, to be hosted by the United Arab Emirates.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The Western Region qualifier was held by the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) in Oman in February 2020 and the Eastern region qualifier was held in Thailand from 29 February to 6 March 2020.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] UAE and Kuwait advanced to the main Asia Cup Qualification after reaching the final of the Western Region event and they were joined by Singapore and Hong Kong who finished in the top two positions in the Eastern event.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] These four teams contested the Asia Cup Qualifier to determine the sixth team to take part in the 2022 Asia Cup (joining the five Asian Full Members of the International Cricket Council).
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] China were originally scheduled to take part in the Eastern Region Group, but they withdrew in February 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Bhutan and Myanmar, who were also included in the original schedule, later withdrew their participation.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] On 23 February 2020, Iran played their first ever T20I match, when they faced the United Arab Emirates in Group B of the Western Region qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] All matches in the qualification tournaments had Twenty20 International (T20I) status.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The 2020 ACC Western Region T20 tournament was held from 23 to 27 February 2020 in Muscat, Oman, and acted as a first qualifying stage for the 2020 Asia Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Bahrain, Kuwait, Maldives, Oman, Saudi Arabia and the UAE all announced their squads for the tournament.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Following the conclusion of the group stage matches of the Western Region, Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar and the UAE had all progressed to the semi-finals.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] An incredible six-wicket win for Bahrain over Qatar in the final group match saw them climb to the top of Group A, with both teams progressing to the semi-finals at the expense of favourites Oman by virtue of slightly better net run rates.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Kuwait and the UAE won their respective semi-final matches to advance to the final of the Western Region group and to the Asia Cup Qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] United Arab Emirates went on to win the final by 102 runs.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The 2020 ACC Eastern Region T20 tournament took place from 29 February to 6 March 2020 in Bangkok, Thailand, and acted as a first qualifying stage for the 2020 Asia Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] It was the first official men's T20I tournament to be played in Thailand.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] China were initially due to play in the Eastern Region tournament, but were forced to withdraw due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Bhutan and Myanmar were also included in the original schedule, but later withdrew.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Hong Kong, Malaysia, Nepal and Singapore all announced their squads for the tournament, with Aizaz Khan, Ahmad Faiz, Gyanendra Malla and Amjad Mahboob as their respective captains.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The opening day of the tournament saw the hosts beaten by Singapore, followed by a surprise defeat for the much-fancied Nepal against Malaysia, who came into the event on the back of a 5–0 series whitewash against Hong Kong.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Nepal were beaten again on day two, this time by Hong Kong, and Thailand also suffered a second defeat with Malaysia taking a second victory.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Singapore thrashed the in-form Malaysians by 128 runs on day three thanks to an unbeaten 92 from just 32 balls for Tim David, and they were joined by Hong Kong on a record of two wins from two matches after their comfortable victory over Thailand.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] After the penultimate round of matches, Nepal were eliminated despite Sandeep Lamichhane bowling a world record 22 dot ball deliveries in their victory over Thailand, due to Singapore's 16-run win over Hong Kong.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The result also secured Singapore's qualification, and meant that the game between Hong Kong and Malaysia on the final day would determine the remaining place in the Asia Cup Qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Singapore won the tournament unbeaten with seven points, after their last fixture against Nepal was abandoned due to rain.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Hong Kong's victory over Malaysia in the last match of the tournament secured their qualification.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Singapore's Tim David was named player of the tournament, while compatriot Sidhant Singh and Hong Kong's Aftab Hussain won the batting and bowling awards, respectively.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The four-team Asia Cup Qualifier was originally scheduled to take place in Kuala Lumpur in August 2020.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The qualifier was held in Oman in August 2022, immediately before the Asia Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Kuwait and the UAE reached the final of the Western Region group, and as a result, also advanced to the Asia Cup Qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Singapore and Hong Kong finished as the top two teams in the Eastern Region group, joining Kuwait and the UAE in the Asia Cup Qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] However, in July 2020, the Asia Cup was postponed to June 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] The Asia Cup was again postponed to August and September 2022, with the qualifier started on 20 August 2022.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Originally scheduled to take place in Sri Lanka, both the Qualifier and the Asia Cup were moved to Oman and the UAE respectively due to the economic and political crisis in Sri Lanka.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2020-acc-eastern-region-t20] Hong Kong qualified for the main event after a first-place finish in the qualifier.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-challenger-cup] The **2024 ACC Men's Challenger Cup**, the second edition of the ACC Men's Challenger Cup, was played in Thailand in January and February 2024.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-challenger-cup] All of the matches had Twenty20 International (T20I) status, and the tournament was a part of the qualification pathway for the 2025 Asia Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-challenger-cup] Cambodia and Saudi Arabia qualified for the Premier Cup by winning their respective semi-final matches.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-challenger-cup] Singapore beat Japan by 8 wickets in the third-place play-off.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-challenger-cup] Saudi Arabia beat Cambodia by 5 wickets in the final.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-challenger-cup] The victory meant that Saudi Arabia retained the trophy, having won the 50-over format tournament in 2023.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] The **2024 ACC Men's Premier Cup** was the second edition of ACC Premier Cup, took place in April 2024.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] It served as the final stage of qualification for the 2025 Asia Cup Tournament.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] UAE won the tournament by defeating Oman in the final, and thus qualified for the 2025 Asia Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] It featured the 8 highest-ranked ACC associate members who were joined by two finalists from 2024 ACC Men's Challenger Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] Cambodia and Saudi Arabia qualified for the tournament after finishing as the top two teams in the 2024 ACC Men's Challenger Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] Nepal were the defending champions, having won the 2023 edition (which was a One Day International tournament).
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] Following teams were qualified for the tournament.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-men-s-premier-cup] The 10 participating nations were divided into two groups, with top two teams from each group advancing to the knockout stage.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-under-19-women-s-t20-asia-cup] India also named Hurley Gala, Happy Kumari, G Kavya Sree, Gayatri Survase as standbys and Prapti Raval as non-travelling reserve.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-under-19-women-s-t20-asia-cup] Sri Lanka also named Nethangi Isuranjali as their travelling reserves.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The **2024 ACC Women's Premier Cup** was the inaugural edition of the ACC Women's Premier Cup, hosted by Malaysia in February 2024.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The tournament was a part of the qualification pathway for 2024 Women's Twenty20 Asia Cup.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] The Asian Cricket Council announced the complete fixtures for the tournament on 16 January 2024.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] Four semi-finalists Malaysia, Nepal, Thailand and United Arab Emirates qualified for the 2024 Women's Twenty20 Asia Cup, after it had been originally announced that only the finalists (UAE and Malaysia) would qualify.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] UAE defeated Malaysia in the final by 37 runs.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] Ahead of the tournament, Malaysia and Kuwait contested a three-match T20I series.
[src:asian-cricket-council/2024-acc-women-s-premier-cup] Updated to match(es) played on 13 February 2024.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] The **Asian Cricket Council** (**ACC**) is the sport governing body of cricket in most countries and territories in Asia.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] The ACC was established in 1983, to promote and develop the sport of Cricket in Asia.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Subordinate to the International Cricket Council, the council is the continent's regional administrative body, and currently consists of 30 member associations.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Mohsin Naqvi is the current president of Asian Cricket Council.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] The council was formed as the Asian Cricket Conference in New Delhi, India, on 19 September 1983, with the original members being Bangladesh, India, Malaysia, Pakistan, Singapore, and Sri Lanka.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Changing its name to the present in 1995.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Until 2003, the headquarters of the council were rotated biennially amongst the presidents' and secretaries' home countries.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] The organization's current president is Mohsin Naqvi.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Previously ACC was headquartered in Colombo, Sri Lanka, which was officially opened on 20 August 2016.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] In 2019, the headquarters of the ACC was moved to Dubai, near the International Cricket Council (ICC) office.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Bangladesh became associate member of ICC in 1977, and later promoted to Full Member in 2000.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Sri Lanka became associate member of ICC in 1965, before getting Full Membership in 1981.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Sri Lanka was also the first associate member to get full member status.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Indonesia has ACC membership while still remaining a part of ICC EAP region for ICC events qualification pathways.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Japan has ACC membership while still remaining a part of ICC EAP region for ICC events qualification pathways.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Japan was also a member of the ACC between 1996–2001.
[src:asian-cricket-council/asian-cricket-council] Philippines has ACC membership while still remaining a part of ICC EAP region for ICC events qualification pathways.
